A 30-year -old, right-hand-dominant
content: A 30-year -old, right-hand-dominant man presents to the clinic complaining of anterior right shoulder pain. There is pain mostly with an overhead movement that radiates to the biceps muscle belly. He takes no medications, is otherwise healthy, and works as a car mechanic. He is an avid volleyball player. His examination includes a positive Hawkins test, positive Yerguson's test, tenderness to palpation over the intertubercular sulcus, and a negative Speed's test. The rest of the examination is normal. Plain radiographs are normal.

title: An active, 19-year-old gymnast
content: An active, 19-year-old gymnast complains of ulnar-sided wrist pain.  She has already obtained an MRI scan which reveals ECU tendinitis.

title: A 7-year-old boy arrives at the emergency
content: A 7-year-old boy arrives at the emergency department with forearm pain. Today he was picking up his backpack when he felt a pop in his forearm that resulted in the current injury.  His history is significant for 5 other fractures treated nonsurgically. His mother states that she had 14 fractures during childhood but is healthy now. Both the boy and his mother have blue sclera.  Figures above are the radiographs of his injured forearm.

title: A 56-year -old homemaker fell down the steps
content: A 56-year -old homemaker fell down the steps of her basement injuring her left ring finger. She was seen at an outside facility with significant deformity of the ring finger. There were no open wounds. There were severe pain and limited motion. Radiographs are shown in Figures above.

title: A 43-year -old man was struck by a car
content:
A 43-year -old man was struck by a car while walking along the road. Neurologic examination demonstrates 5/5 strength in all muscle groups in his upper extremities but 0/5 strength throughout the lower extremities. Though sensation throughout the lower extremities is absent, he has diminished yet present perianal sensation to light touch and pinprick. His imaging studies are shown in figures above.

In the trauma bay, the patient 's blood pressure suddenly drops to 80/50 mm Hg while his pulse increases to 120 bpm. One liter fluid bolus of lactated Ringers is infused which normalizes his blood pressure and pulse.

title: A 25-year-old worker reporting back pain and weakness
content: A 25-year-old worker reporting back pain and weakness of both legs after felt down from top of the roof. The physical examination finding stable hemodynamic and he still able to move both lower leg with motoric power 3/5. AP X-ray view is shown in figure above.

title: A 66 years old male , unable to walk for the
content: A 66 years old male , unable to walk for the past six months and weakness of both hand, no history of trauma . Increasing of knee jerk and positive babinsky test are noted. Hoffman Tromner test are positive . The cervical x ray shown above

His body mass index is 32, and he has had these symptoms for 10 days.

title: A 40-year-old man who arrives at the emergency department with a 4-day
content: A 40-year-old man who arrives at the emergency department with a 4-day history of fevers and severe back pain without radiation. He is normotensive at presentation with a heart rate of 86 beats per minute. Upon examination he is neurologically intact with normal sensory and motor function. He has a history of alcohol and cocaine abuse. His white blood cell (WBC) count is 12000 (reference range [rr], 4500-11000/ μL) and his C-reactive protein (CRP) level is 100 mg/L (rr, 0.08-3.1 mg/L).

title: Spine 5
content: A 57-year-old woman who has had 3 months of back pain that radiates into her left anterolateral thigh, anterior shin, and medial ankle. Her pain has persisted after participating in physical therapy and receiving medications and an epidural injection. She has a positive straight-leg raise result and weakness in the left ankle dorsoflexion

title: Spine 4

title: Spine 3
content: A  65 -year-old woman  has main complain back pain and  radiating pain  into both legs. Her pain improves with bending forward or lying flat and worsens with ambulation. Her neurologic examination reveals 4/5 strength in ankle dorsiflexion, but otherwise is unremarkable. She has attempted nonsurgical care including physical therapy and medications for 6 months.

title: Adult recon 3
content: A 30-y.o healthy man who sustained  an anterior R-shoulder dislocation while playing baseball. He requires a closed reduction under sedation at a local EMG dept. He is placed into a shoulder immobilizer and referred to your office for further treatment. Upon inquiry, the patient states that he previously dislocated the shoulder twice within the last year while playing.  X-ray result is normal. He demonstrates positive apprehension and speed tests.

title: BE12018-3
content: Figures above are the radiographs of a 50-year-old man who has pain radiating into both legs since 6 months ago. His back pain worsened  with bending forward and ambulation and muscle atrophy are noted at his lower leg. His neurologic examination reveals normal strength in ankle dorsiflexion, but  3/5 in ankle plantar flexion.

title: BE12018-4
content: A 22-year-old man has a cervical fracture-dislocation after being involved in a motor vehicle collision. Examination reveals normal sensation in his upper extremities and strength that is graded as 5/5 in his biceps, 4/5 in wrist extensors, 4/5 in triceps, and 0/5 in his hands and inferior extremities muscles. With preservation of pinprick sensation only at perianal region

title: BE12018-8
content: This is the MR image of a 43-year-old woman with a 3-week history of neck pain radiating into her left arm. She denies weakness, or problems with balance. Examination reveals her pain is reproduced with ipsilateral neck rotation.

title: BE12018-9
content: This is cervical spine x-ray of a 25-year-old man who has neck pain and tetraplegia after a motor vehicle collision.

title: BE12018-11
content: This is an axial MR image of a 34-year-old woman who has had severe right leg pain for 3 months. The pain starts in her back and radiates into her posterior thigh, lateral shin, and dorsum of the foot. Examination reveals a positive right straight-leg raise result, weakness (4/5) in the right extensor hallucis longus, and numbness in her great toe.

title: BE12018-12
content: These are CT scan and MR image of a 60-year-old woman who fell at home. She has severe back pain after trauma. Examination reveals severe thoracic kyphosis, but the motor and sensory functions are normal.

title: BE12018-13
content: This is the lateral radiograph of the lumbosacral junction and pelvis of a 67-year-old woman with a lumbar deformity who is being evaluated for surgery.

title: BE12018-41
content: Six month before coming to the clinic, an 80-year-old male sustained an open fracture on his left tibia but refuse any medical treatment. Today the patient come again to the hospital with pus draining from the wound and inability to walk. After thorough evaluation, you diagnose this patient with chronic osteomyelitis and non-union of the left tibia due to neglected untreated open fracture Cierny stage 3 type B.

title: BE12018-42
content: A 53-year-old male arrives in the trauma bay with a GCS 15 and hemodynamically stable following a high-speed motor vehicle crash. He is complaining of severe right hip pain and is unable to move his right lower extremity. You note that his leg is shortened, slightly flexed, internally rotated, and adducted. He has symmetric pulses, and he is neurologically intact throughout his extremity. He has a normal examination otherwise. As part of the standard Advanced Trauma Life Support algorithm, an an AP pelvis is obtained seen in figure below (Picture 1)

title: BE12018-43
content: A 26-year-old man involved in a high-speed motor vehicle collision arrives to the emergency department with an obvious deformity of the right leg. Orthogonal radiographs of the right tibia/fibula are depicted in figures below. An initial assessment deems the patient to be stable with no evidence of associated intrathoracic or intra-abdominal injuries. The skin is intact, there are palpable pulses distally, soft compartments, and the patient is deemed suitable for operative treatment

title: BE12018-44
content: A 55-year-old man complains of right ankle pain and inability to bear weight after he fell down a hill while mowing his lawn. AP and lateral radiographs of the right ankle demonstrate a spiral fracture of the fibula at the level of the plafond.

title: BE12018-45
content: A 49-year-old female with stage IV breast cancer presents to your office with worsening left hip pain. A recent bone scan ordered by her oncologist identifies multiple lesions in the spine, right humeral shaft, left clavicle, right ilium, and left proximal femur. She recently underwent radiation to the spine, left proximal femur, and right humeral shaft.

title: BE12018-46
content: A 16-year-old female sprains her ankle playing Soccer and is brought to the emergency room. X-rays are negative for fracture, but an orthopaedic consult is placed to evaluate a suspicious lesion in the distal tibia. Prior to her acute ankle injury, she denies any pain in her lower leg. Her father died at a young age of colon cancer, and she is anxious about this finding being suggestive of malignancy. X-ray is shown in figure below.

title: BE12018-47
content: A 55-year-old man with a long history of type 2 diabetes presents with a swollen, erythematous, hot, and mildly tender right foot. The majority of his erythema is localized in his midfoot. He reports that he has had increased pain in his foot for the past week. He has been doing his regular foot care without any skin breakdown. In addition, he has had no fevers, chills, or elevated blood sugars. On physical examination his vital signs are stable. He has swelling in his right foot, but no visible ulcer. His pulse is strongly palpable, but he has decreased sensation bilaterally in a stocking distribution to the level of the mid tibia. In addition to concern for infection you wish to evaluate the patient for Charcot foot.

title: BE12018-48
content: The patient is a 68-year-old, right-handed male who presents to the emergency department following a tablesaw injury to his nondominant left index finger. The patient states that he was working at home after having “a few” beers, when his hand slipped and his nondominant index finger was drawn into the blade of the saw. On examination, he has sustained an amputation to the index finger at the mid-shaft of the proximal phalanx, with a stellate, multilevel soft tissue injury to the index finger base. Radiographs demonstrate a comminuted fracture of the proximal phalanx with intra-articular involvement and a fracture of the metacarpal head. The amputated index finger was irretrievable and not brought to the hospital.

title: BE12018-56
content: A 50-year-old female with multiple joint pain of the hand and feet. She experienced the pain symmetrically for the last 8 weeks and more in the proximal part of the joint. The pain is usually worsened early in the morning accompanied with stiffness after a period of inactivity. After lab exam and x-ray examination, the orthopedic surgeon diagnoses her with rheumatoid arthritis of the hand in the synovitis stage.

title: BE12018-55
content: A 50-year-old female with multiple joint pain of the hand and feet. She experienced the pain symmetrically for the last 8 weeks and more in the proximal part of the joint. The pain is usually worsened early in the morning accompanied by stiffness after a period of inactivity. After lab exam and x-ray examination, the orthopedic surgeon diagnoses her with rheumatoid arthritis of the hand in the synovitis stage.

title: BE12018-53
content: An 11-year-old girl came to the clinic with chief complain a crooked back. She has not had her period (menarche) yet. The physical examination showed that she still has a balanced shoulder with a prominent hump on the right thoracic area. X-ray evaluation depicts a structural thoracal curve apex in T8 with Cobb angle of 65◦ and non-structural lumbar curve apex in L3 with Cobb angle of 30◦. Further evaluation showed that the apex of the lumbar curve is still within central sacral line between the pedicles. Thoracic sagittal profile showed 20◦ of thoracic kyphosis.

title: BE12018-52
content: A 6-year-old female comes to the clinic with her mother observing a thickening and slight enlargement on both of her knees with some bowing deformity.  The enlargement is not severely progressive, however there also same bumps found around the wrist, the ankle and around the costochondral junction. Her mother also noticed that her child has smaller body compared to her friends.

title: BE12018-51
content: A six-year-old boy has been diagnosed with cerebral palsy and limited ambulatory function. Your physical exam found mild spasticity in all four extremities, with more involvement in the lower extremity compares to the upper extremities. The cognitive function of the patient is only mildly delayed for his chronologic age. In the pelvis radiograph, you found signs of dysplasia on bilateral hips.

title: BE12018-62
content: A 45-year-old man is brought to the trauma bay after falling from his roof while cleaning his utters. He complains of severe lower back pain but is neurologically intact. Initial CT images demonstrate an L1 burst fracture with a fracture through the lamina, 50% canal compromise from bony retropulsion, and 25 degrees of segmental kyphosis. An MRI demonstrates discontinuity of the ligamentum flavum and interspinous ligaments at the injured level.

title: BE12018-50
content: An 83-year-old female with a history of THR performed 14 years ago presents after an acute fall. She has a 2 year history of increasing thigh pain that initially began atraumatically. Figure below reveals a hip radiograph taken 1 month prior to the fall when she returned to her orthopaedic surgeon complaining of thigh pain. She has been unable to ambulate since the fall and presents to the emergency department for evaluation with new radiographs as seen figures below.

title: BE12018-51
content: A 37-year-old, male motorcyclist was struck by another vehicle at highway speeds. He was intubated in the field. On arrival to the trauma bay his GCS is 3T, heart rate is 130 beats per minute, blood pressure is 90/58 mm Hg, lactate is 8, and his base deficit is 6. He is found to have a grade IV splenic laceration, multiple rib fractures, a pelvic ring injury, a closed left femur fracture, a comminuted Gustilo–Anderson 3C tibia fracture, and a small intraparenchymal hemorrhage. He is stabilized in the trauma bay and taken directly to the operating room by the general surgery team for exploratory laparotomy.

title: BE12018-52
content: A 42-year-old man presents to the hospital with pain and swelling of the dorsum of his hand. He reports blunt trauma against a metal shelf, but does not remember a break in the skin. There is a blister of the skin. He reports erythema started approximately 6 hours ago of the hand but it now extends to the wrist. He is febrile to 102 degrees, heart rate is 110, and blood pressure is 92/38. He has significant pain to palpation and induration of the dorsum of the hand.

title: BE12018-A1
content: This is a Radiological picture of a 53-year-old male with a left hip pain felt since 4 months before admission. The pain felt insidious, occurred when he was walking, decreased when resting. Now, he feels pain when he raises his leg. Walks with crutches. Fever (-),  history of trauma (-), Cough (-), TB medication (-), alcohol (-) no history of the family member with the same disease, history of traditional medicine consumption and analgesic (+) since 5 years ago. Physical examination shows leg length discrepancy and tenderness on the right hip without mass and swelling. The range of motion was limited (see the picture above). Laboratory examination was performed with result, WBC 11.700, ESR 25, CRP 0,4, uric acid 21/23, and ICT TB was negative.

title: BE12018-A2
content: A-70-years old female complaining bilateral knee pain since 10 years ago. Pain is felt when she is walking and climbing the stairs. She also feels her leg is become bowed. No history of trauma. Clinical and radiological pictures show in the figure above. Varus deformity, patellar crepitation and limited range of motion were found in physical examination.

title: BE12018-A3
content: This is the clinical and radiological picture of a 68 y.o. female. She complained of thigh pain after slipping on the floor at home. She had a history of hip pain treated by herself using traditional medicine and painkillers since 33 years ago. She underwent total hip replacement 31 years ago because of a damaged hip (exact diagnosis is unknown)

title: BE12018-A4
content: This is the radiological and clinical picture of a 45 y.o. male with a chief complaint of swelling and discomfort on his right knee. He is unable to flex his knee maximally. No history of trauma or fever. He also felt a palpable mass on his right inguinal. Physical examination shows valgus deformity with edema and muscle atrophy, tenderness, warmth, doughy sign positive, no sinus, and range of motion from 5-90 degrees. Patellar tap test was positive. Laboratory test found Hb 11,6 gr/dl, WBC 7,37, ESR 77, CRP 2,2 and ICT TB was positive.

title: BE12018-A5
content: This is the clinical and radiological picture of a 25 y.o male. He came with a complaint of a right knee pain and instability. There is a history of a direct trauma to the knee in a motorcycle accident 6 months ago. Physical examination shows posterior sagging and muscle atrophy, no tenderness, normal neurovascular distal, and range of motion from 0-120 degrees. The special test was performed with result anterior drawer test -/-, Lachman test -/-, posterior drawer test +++/-, and quadriceps active test +/-.

title: BE12018-S3
content: This figure above shows fluoroscopy finding during interventional pain management;

title: BE12018-S4
content: The picture above is A lateral Lumbar Spine X-ray

title: BE18718-UNHAS3
content: A 44 year old, right-hand-dominant, male, sustains blunt trauma to his right arm while using a jackhammer. He has immediate pain and deformity to his right upper extremity and presents immediately to the emergency department with this isolated injury. Physical examination shows skin to be intact, and patient has wrist extensor weakness. Plain radiographs reveal a spiral fracture of the right humerus mid-diaphysis with 30 degrees of anterior and 30 degrees of varus angulation.

title: BE18718-UNHAS6
content: A 50-year-old otherwise healthy and active gentleman fell from a height of approximately 8 ft while rock climbing. He had immediate pain in his left ankle an was unable to bear weight on that extremity. He presented to the emergency department with pain isolated to the left ankle and foot. Initial radiographs of the left ankle are obtained and the lateral view is shown.

title: BE18718-UNHAS11
content: A 78-year-old woman is complaining of a new onset of mid-thoracic back pain after a fall from standing 2 days ago. She denies any radiating pain or paresthesias into the extremities. Physical examination demonstrates that she is neurologically intact and has localized tenderness over the thoracic spine. She remains ambulatory and has adequate pain relief with over-the-counter medications. Thoracic spine radiographs are shown in figure.

title: BE18718-UNHAS12
content: A 76-year-old, right-hand-dominant man presents to clinic complaining of right shoulder pain. The pain started several months ago, has gotten progressively worse and is located diffusely over his deltoid region. He has night pain and pain with overhead activity. On examination, there is no visible muscle atrophy, and he has full passive and near full active range of motion. He experiences pain and some weakness with resisted shoulder forward flexion and abduction.

title: BE18718-UNHAS13
content: A patient presents with a history of chronic wrist pain of 6 years duration. He stated that he sustained a fall 9 years ago. Immediately after injury, he did not seek any medical attention, thinking that he had merely sprained his wrist.

title: BE18718-UNHAS14
content: A 57-year-old female presents to the office with atraumatic knee pain. Her pain is worse at the beginning of activities as well as the end of the day. She has trouble ascending and descending stairs. She uses anti-inflammatories intermittently with mild relief. On examination she has pain along the medial joint line but full range of motion. X-rays show characteristic medial joint space narrowing, subchondral sclerosis, and cysts.

title: BE18718-UNHAS15
content: A 56-year-old male is referred to your office by his primary physician, with concern for metastatic disease. He has lytic lesions found throughout his skeleton, including in the left iliac crest and proximal femur. The iliac crest lesion is biopsied for diagnosis confirmation. Histology image is shown above (GAMBAR 1)

title: BE18718-UNHAS16
content: An 7-year-old girl is brought to the ER by her mother after she fell from the monkey bars during recess at school. She had immediate pain, deformity, and swelling of the elbow after the fall. Upon arrival to the ER, the following radiographs were obtained.

title: BE18718-UNS1
content: Preoperative MRI images are shown from a 67-year-old woman with neck pain, bilateral upper extremity paresthesias, progressively worsening balance, several falls, and increasing problems in both hands with dropping objects. Figure 1 is a sagittal view, Figure 2 is an axial cut at C2-3, Figure below is an axial cut at C5-6, and Figure 4 is an axial cut at C6-7. The patient’s motor strength is grade 4+ of 5 in the bilateral upper extremities.

title: BE18718-UGM1
content: A 25-year-old obese male is sent to your hospital with a diagnosis of bilateral close fracture of the femoral shaft following a road traffic accident. During the primary survey in the ER, you noticed that the patient looks pale with a confused and irritable condition. The extremities are cold with HR: 128 x/minutes, BP: 90/60 mmHg and urine output 15cc/Kg BW/ Hour. After the fluid resuscitation, the patient’s condition improves and both of the extremity are put in a traction for provisional immobilization

title: BE18718-UGM2
content: A 45-year-old male has a motorcycle accident and is diagnosed as Left tibial plateau fracture Schatzker 6. In the emergency department, the patient was put in a long leg posterior splint and scheduled for internal fixation the next morning

title: BE18718-UGM3
content: A 34-year-old male come to the orthopedic outpatient clinic with a chief complain of pain and deformity in his back. The pain started with discomfort since 6 months ago and increase as time goes by, predominantly during activity and relieve in resting. He also felt general weakness, night sweats and weight loss with visible a hard lump in the middle part of the back. Your physical finding showed kyphosis with apex around Th 11 with a decrease of ASIA score distal to Th 12 level. The laboratory examination suggests tuberculosis with MRI showing increase T2 weighted image in Th11-12 with abscess formation surrounding the vertebrae and narrowing the spinal canal.

title: BE18718-UGM4
content: A 56-year-old female came to the orthopedic outpatient clinic with a chief of complaint of severe pain in her back with numbness and weakness on both of the lower extremity. From the history taking you notice that the patient was diagnosed with DDD and protrusion of the L4-L5 disc that underwent transforaminal injection 2 weeks prior to admission. From the MRI you noticed increased intensity throughout the L4-L5 disc with the posterior epidural extension that encroaches the canal. The laboratory examination showed leucocyte count 21.300/mm3 and ESR 15 mg/ml

title: BE18718-UGM5
content: A 45-year-old male patient comes with main complain of disturbed gait with increased stiffness on both of lower extremity. The complaint is felt on activity and progress over time, 3 months before the disturbed walk he felt the loss of dexterity and have difficulties in buttoning his shirt. From the physical examination, you found that the patient is still able to ambulate independently without walking aid. You also found shuffling gait with increase physiologic reflex on both of lower extremity. From the supporting examination, you find continuous extending ossification of the PLL from C3 to C6 that narrowed the spinal canal.

title: BE18718-UGM6
content: A 65-year-old lady comes to your clinic for the second opinion related to the condition of her knee. She was previously diagnosed with osteoarthritis of the left knee and told to have a knee replacement, due to some hesitation she comes to your clinic to ask for more information. She is an active lady (normal BMI) that still do some Tennis on her spare time, however, during the last 6 months, she often feels knee pain the next morning after playing Tennis. The physical examination showed that her BMI is normal and the ROM of the knee is good. Her x-ray suggests mild osteophyte formation with slight narrowing in the medial part of the knee. She told you that she never take any medicine of physiotherapy related to her complain

title: BE18718-UGM7
content: A 35-year-old male wrestler comes to your clinic with a chief of complain pain and bulging in the anterior part of his knee. The pain is felt during kneeling position due to bulging mass on the anterior part of his patella. He complained that the mass occurred about 3 days ago after kneeling exercise and feel pain afterward. From physical examination, you feel smooth round mass with a diameter of 3 cm on the anterior part of the patella with mobile and fluctuation of the mass.

title: BE18718-UGM8
content: A 13-year-old girl presents with an isolated distal femur mass that was diagnosed as osteosarcoma. From the radiologic investigation, the mass has already extended into the surrounding soft tissue. Further work-up is negative for metastasis, with biopsy reveals a high-grade lesion.

title: BE18718-H1
content: 37 yo male, right-hand-dominant male is referred to the ER after sustaining injury on his left ring finger.

title: BE18718-H2
content: A 29 y.o. male sustained injury to his right elbow during Motor Vehicle Accident. The X-ray of this elbow shown below.

title: BE18718-H3
content: 40 y.o. male worked in Factory got his left hand trapped in machinery for 2 hours. He managed to release his hand afterwards. He felt excruciating pain and can’t feel his fingers. Analgetic given only gave little relieve of his pain.

title: BE18718-H4
content: 21 y.o. Male, Right handed, suffered injury into his left thumb during soccer game. He is a keeper, and got forced thumb abduction when catching the ball.

title: BE18718-H5
content: A patient presents with a history of chronic wrist pain of 5 years duration. He sustained a fall 9 years ago. Immediately after injury, he did not seek any medical attention, thinking that he had merely sprained his wrist.

title: BE18718-H6
content:
A 71 y o male complaining 2-year history of bilateral hand pain. He has morning stiffness in both of his hands, which lasts longer than 1 hour. No trauma to the hands before.
The pain is mostly in his PIP and MCP of both hands. He has general aches and pains all over, but the hands are the worst.
There is swollen, tender PIP and MCP joints bilaterally with some ulnar deviation. The DIP joints seem to be normal. He also has a small, nontender, rubbery nodule near his elbow. Neurovascular exam is normal.

title: BE18718-H7
content:
A 33 y.o. Male sustained a gunshot wound at the elbow joint 10 months ago. No fracture was seen, and he has had no surgery. Now he complains of the inability to fully extend the wrist and all digits.
 
Physical exam reveals 5/5 elbow flexion and extension but no function of the wrist extensors, EDC, or extensor pollicis longus.
 
He has diminished sensation on the dorsal aspect of the radial hand and thumb. He has full passive ROM of the digits and wrist flexion and lacks 10 degrees of passive wrist extension.

title: BE18718-A1
content: A 75 year old male underwent total knee arthroplasty due to osteoarthritis of the right knee. During the surgery, after trial of the implant, the patella subluxes laterally during flexion.

title: BE18718-A2
content: A 61 years old lady complained about pain on her left hip due to osteoarthritis. She underwent elective hybrid total hip replacement surgery under combine spinal epidural anaesthesia. During the surgery, upon insertion of the femoral stem, her heart rate suddenly drop from 100 to 55 per minute, oxygen saturation fell to 76% and she became unresponsive.

title: BE18718-A3
content: A 25 years old male complains of ‘giving way’ feeling on the right knee. 3 weeks ago, his knee was swollen after falling down and hit the ground when he was playing basketball. From the physical examination at the time of the injury, by looking there’s asymmetric knee, hyperemia, swelling (+), feel tenderness (+), and  limited range of movement, lack of extension. From the special test: Balotement (+), Cross fluctuation test (+), Patellar tap test (+)

title: BE18718-A4
content: A 69 years old female presents with swelling and pain on her calf 8 days after total knee arthroplasty. Clinical picture showed that there’s swelling (+), bruise (+), tenderness (+), palpable distal pulse (+), and limited range of motion. From the special test: Homan’s sign (+), squeeze test (+). D-Dimer level = 3 ug/ml

title: BE18718-A5
content: A 45-year-old gentlemen presented with pain and swelling in the arm after arm wrestling with his neighbor, around two months ago.

title: BE18718-O1
content: A 30-years-old male complaining lump in his right wrist joint since 9 months ago.

title: BE18718-O2
content: A 50-years old male suddenly suffering severe pain on his bilateral arm

title: BE18718-03
content: A 35-years old female comes to private clinic with pain and lump on her left ankle joint since 10 months ago.

title: BE18718-O4
content: A 53-years old female have mild pain on his right hip since 2 months. She was diagnosed with breast carcinoma 1 year ago and underwent surgery and chemotherapy.

title: BE18718-P1
content: A 6 yo child fell down 1,5 years ago while playing football, he was brought to a bonesetter and was splinted for 6 weeks. Up until now he still feels his left elbow is unstable

title: BE18718-P2
content: A 11 yo boy had an antalgic gait since a few months ago. There was no history of hip major trauma. The gait got worst and he now barely walks. Left hips reveals significant limitations of internal rotation and abduction.

title: BE18718-P3
content: A 8 year old boy presented with short stature and bilateral genu valgus. Laboratory shows elevated serum phosphatase alkaline (2000 IU/L)

title: BE18718-P4
content: A 15 year old female with history of prematurity and prolonged ventilatory assisted hospitalization in NICU, presented to your clinic with spastic muscles, wheel chair dependendent and anxiety most likely due to hip pain

title: BE18718-P5
content: A 12 yo boy presented to your clinic with discharging sinus for the last 5 years. There was a history of fell down, fever and swollen right knee before it started to discharge

title: BE18718-S1
content: This is  a CT scan imaging of a 27 years old male suffered from total paraplegia of both lower extremities after RTA

title: BE18718-S2
content: A 69-year-old woman  has  gait and balance difficulties after falling down. Physical examination reveals  weakness in  upper extremity weakness (1/5) and lower extremity (3/5). The MRI result shown above

title: BE18718-S3
content: In spinal column biomechanics

title: BE18718-S4
content: These are the radiograph and CT and MRI scans of a 35-year-old man with diabetes mellitus.  He had severe neck pain for 6 weeks.  He now has fevers and progressive weakness and numbness in his upper extremities.  Examination reveals 3/5 strength in both upper extremities, with decreased sensation in both arms and hands and hyperreflexia.

title: BE18718-S5
content: These are the lumbar CT scans of a 16-year-old baseball pitcher who has had low-back pain for 3 months.  He has no radiating pain, numbness, or weakness.  His pain is worsened by extension and relieved with flexion.  Examination reveals normal strength and sensation in his lower extremities.

title: BE18718-UI2
content: A 5-year-old boy has been febrile for the past 2 days, after an upper respiratory tract infection 7 days ago. He refuses to walk when you see him in your consultation room. He holds his left leg in frog legged position (The hip is flexed, externally rotated and abducted) and he will not let you examine him. His temperature is 39°C while his white cell count is 20. 000 WBC/mm 3, Erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR) is 60 mm/h, and C-reactive protein (CRP) is 70 mg/dL.

title: BE18718-UI3
content: A 7-year-old boy comes to your clinic because he started to be running strangely when playing outside a few weeks ago. Eventhough there is no sigificant major trauma to the hip, the problem got worst since then and he now walks with shorter steps with his left leg and spends less of the stance phase on that limb. Examination of bilateral hips reveals significant limitations of left hip in internal and external rotation and abduction. The x ray is as follows

title: BE18718-UI4
content: A 12-year-old girl comes to your clinic as a wheelchair-dependent and spastic child. She has a history of anoxia as an infant and prolonged hospitalization in NICU under ventilator. Hip abduction of the left hip is less than 30°, Tardieu scale R1-R2 less than 15°. The pelvic x ray is as follow

title: BE18718-UI5
content: The emergency department calls you to see a 12-year-old male with pain on his proximal left  thigh. He was hit by a car while riding bycycle this morning. He refuses to move his left hip joint. The CT scan is as follow

title: BE18718-UI6
content: A 4 year old girl comes to your clinic unable to flex her left elbow after a fall in the playground 2 days ago. There is a slight tenderness on the lateral part of the elbow. The x ray is as follow

title: ELECTIVE BALI 1
content: A 4 months old baby with the deformity on both of his feet. The baby is active and able to roll over.

title: BE191218-HAND1
content: A 42 years old female maid complaining pain at her radial sided wrist, she denies previous trauma

title: BE191218-HAND2
content:
An 18-months-old boy comes to your office accompanied by his parents who have recently noticed that while he is using his hand, he appears unable to extend his thumb fully.

The child is able to use his hand very well, does not appear to be in any pain. The x-ray is shown no abnormality.

title: BE191218-HAND3
content: A boy, 10 y.o, came with prominence in front of right elbow. History of trauma 3 years ago after fell from his bike. No pain with full ROM

title: BE191218-hand4
content:
A 34-year-old man presents to the emergency department with pain in his left small finger. He reports that he was cutting meat when his knife slipped and punctured the volar surface of his proximal phalanx. It did not bleed, and he did not seek further medical treatment.

He presents with pain in passive extension of the finger, fusiform swelling.

title: BE191218-HAND5
content:
A 50 year old male. Patient with mid shaft humerus fracture nine months ago. Without radial nerve lesion

Prior U-slab fixation.

Patient refused surgery.

title: BE191218-SPINE1
content: Male 26 years old, have a stab wound on posterior of  the neck, after street  fighting  two hours before admission. Physical examination reveal total  right hemiplegia , no abnormal finding in the cranial nerves.

title: BE191218-SPINE2
content: Female 42 years old , come to A&E Dept with  main complain severe pain on right lower  leg and unable to extend the right big toe  ( 2/5, LMN type) and micturition problem

title: BE191218-SPINE3
content: This is  a CT scan imaging of a 27 years old male suffered from total paraplegia of both lower extremities after RTA

title: BE191218-SPINE4
content: Regarding this injury

title: BE191218-SPINE5
content:
A 64-year-old man admitted to A&E Departement with severe back pain since 5 months ago,  but since a weeks ago ,  he got fevers, and chills. He also has difficulty in walking (muscle power 3/5), No history of trauma, he have been suffered of diabetes mellitus since 5 years ago.          

Vital Sign : BP : 120/80, pulse : 98/mnt, RR : 16/mnt, Temperature : 39,8⁰C

Laboratory finding :  Hb : 11,2 ; Leuco :  21.000; ESR: 105 ; Blood Glucose 315 ; Creatinine : 2,4

title: BE191218-10/11
content: Mrs. Heni came to your clinic bring her 2 months baby with right fracture that happened while she taking bath her baby. This is the third time it happened the first on left leg, the second time in on right lower leg. On Examination you find blue sclerae.

title: BE191218-15/16/17/18
content: A 4 year old boy come to the emergency department and diagnose with closed fracture of the left supracondylar humerus extension type Gartland III, From the physical examination you also find swelling and positive Pucker sign in the anterior part of the distal humerus.

title: BE191218-23/24/25/26
content: A 25 year old female was referred to the emergency of your hospital following a RTA. She was a passenger of a car that had a head to head collision with other car. The physical examination of general condition showed the patient look painful with HR: 112x/min, RR: 28x/min, BP: 110/80 mmHg and T: normal. From the spine evaluation you notice loss of sensory and motor function below Th 10 with seatbelt mark on the anterior part of the chest wall. From the x ray you see posterior to anterior disruption with opening of PLC until the 2/3 of vertebral disc between the levels of Th9 – Th10

title: BE191218-27/28/29/30/31
content: A 19 year old female runner come to your clinic with pain and discomfort on her right forefoot. She experienced the pain after following intense training to prepare for a marathon for the last 6 months. The pain is felt on and off in the distal part of the 2nd and 3rd metatarsal, occasionally occurred with swelling after her running practice. Despite the condition after the training the patient still able to perform her daily activity without pain.

title: BE191218-35/36
content: A 23 year old male come to the clinic complaining the 5th time of having a shoulder dislocation. The last dislocation happened after brushing his hair and spontaneously reduce around 5 minutes afterward.

title: BE191218-37/38
content: A mother come to your clinic complaining her 7 day old baby with a flail right upper extremity. She noticed that the baby’s right upper extremity look less active than the left side since after the birth, she also said that it is her first child and the baby birth weight was 4.200 gr with a breech presentation. From the physical examination you found that the shoulder look abnormally adducted and forearm internally rotated.

title: BE191218-51/52
content:
Figures A and B ABOVE are the radiographs of a 70-year-old retired man who falls while skiing and injures his right hip. He had no preceding hip pain. After the fall, he is unable to ambulate and is transferred down the mountain by the ski patrol and taken to a hospital

.

title: BE191218-54/55
content: Figures ABOVE is a boy 4 years old, his parents notice bowing of right leg since birth. There is no trauma before and he also can walk with crutch and  have normal growth. His father has same condition with him, that notice bowing of left leg. This boy have a skin with dark spot of on his body

title: BE191218-57/58/59
content: A 10-year-old girl has right knee pain related to activity. An avid soccer player, she has noted pain after the first 15 minutes of running but no swelling or mechanical symptoms. Radiographs show a large 2-cm osteochondritis dissecans (OCD) lesion.

title: BE191218-71/72/73/74
content: A patient with a history of proximal tibia was hit by a motorcycle 4 hours prior to hospital admission. Primary survey is clear with blood pressure 110/60 mmHg. Clinical picture as shown below, patient had pain on passive stretch of toes. Pulsation of dorsalis pedis artery and tibialis posterior artery are still palpable

title: BE191218-77/78/79
content: Six month before coming to the clinic, an 80-year-old male sustained an open fracture on his left tibia but refuse any medical treatment. Today the patient come again to the hospital with pus draining from the wound and inability to walk. After thorough evaluation, you diagnose this patient with chronic osteomyelitis and non-union of the left tibia due to neglected untreated open fracture Cierny stage 3 type B

title: BE191218-80/81/82/83
content: A 42-year-old man presents to the hospital with pain and swelling of the dorsum of his hand. He reports blunt trauma against a metal shelf, but does not remember a break in the skin. There is a blister of the skin. He reports erythema started approximately 6 hours ago of the hand but it now extends to the wrist. He is febrile to 102 degrees, heart rate is 110, and blood pressure is 92/38. He has significant pain to palpation and induration of the dorsum of the hand

title: BE191218-PED1
content:
A 10 year old boy presented in emergency department after hit by a motorcycle 2 hours before admission. He was unable to move his right lower leg due to pain

The bone fragment on anteromedial was completely detached from soft tissue and could be easily separated off from the remainding bone. Gross meassurement showed that the detached bone fragment is about 50% of the bone circumferential diameter. Neurovascular distal is intact

title: BE191218-PED2
content: A 6 year old boy complain for lack of complete elbow flexion as well as limitation of terminal pronation and supinationon of his right elbow. He has a history of painfull and swollen forearm 3 months ago after a fell. The swelling has already been subsided but the limitation of range of motions persist.

title: BE191218-PED3
content: A one month old baby was brought to your clinic with bilateral crooked feet. The baby had a normal pregnancy and delivery. The baby is aterm and body weight is 3000 gram. Apgar score was 9/10.

title: BE191218-PED4
content: A 5 year old boy came to your clinic with painless, tilted neck since birth. There is no history of cervical trauma or any seizures. The tilted neck was not progressive, the deformity grossly stayed at the same level of severity.  The patient can play, run and jump as like the other children of his age. No treatment had been employed before

title: BE191218-PED5
content: A four year old boy fell when playing football. He had been limping since 6 month beforehand. There was no history of significant trauma before.

title: BE191218-MST1
content: A 15 years-old male complaining lump on his right knee since 2 months ago with moderate pain. He was admitted to hospital for establishing the diagnosis. X-ray, laboratory and biopsy examination was performed two days ago. Hb: 8,0 gr/dl, WB: 9.000 gr/dl, ESR: 40, ALP: 250, LDH: 300

title: BE191218-MST2
content: A 50 years-old female with moderate pain on the right arm since 6 months ago. She had a history of breast carcinoma 3 years ago and finished chemo-radiotherapy cycle 2 years ago. She comes to the hospital for follow up check-up and the doctor was found a lesion on her humerus from the x-ray.

title: BE191218-MST3
content: A 9 years old boy complain pain the left lower leg for three months. There is no history of trauma. An axial cut of CT scan of lower leg and biopsy result was shown on the figures above

title: BE191218-MST4
content: A figure above show pathology on x-ray

title: BE191218-MST5
content: A figure above shows an axial cut of thigh MRI

title: BE191218-AR1
content: A 40-year-old man sustained an injury to left ankle in a traffic accident. A radiograph was taken upon examination in the emergency department

title: BE191218-AR2
content: A 25-year-old football player sustained a twisting injury to his left knee. He has already had a diagnostic arthroscopy in another hospital. He came to you with an MRI result and a printed intra-operative arthroscopic picture to show you for a second opinion.

title: BE191218-AR3
content: A 60-year-old male came with a pain on his right hip. He had a history of prolonged consumption of traditional medicine

title: BE191218-AR4
content: A 63-year-old male came with the swollen, warm and painful right knee. Two weeks ago he underwent a knee replacement surgery. He had a fever and initial blood count showed increased ESR (70 mm/h) and leucocyte count (23.000)

title: BE191218-AR5
content: A 58-year-old female suddenly felt pain on her left hip after falling from a bed. One year ago she had a total hip replacement surgery. The immediate postoperative (picture A) and the current x-ray (picture B) are shown.

title: BE29519-MCQ-1
content: A 34-year-old, right-hand-dominant male is brought to the emergency department by his friends with a chief complaint of right arm pain and deformity. Earlier in the day he was thrown from his dirt bike during an amateur race and attempted to break his fall with his arm. Your examination finds that he is nontender about his elbow but has significant pain and deformity about the forearm and wrist. His radiographs are shown in Figures

title: BE29519-MCQ-3
content: A 37-year-old, male motorcyclist was struck by another vehicle at highway speeds. He was intubated in the field. On arrival to the trauma bay, his GCS is  3-x-3, heart rate is 130 beats per minute, blood pressure is 90/58 mm Hg, lactate is 8, and his base deficit is 6. He is found to have a grade IV splenic laceration, multiple rib fractures, a pelvic ring injury, a closed left femur fracture, a comminuted Gustilo–Anderson 3C tibia fracture. He is stabilized in the trauma bay and taken directly to the operating room by the general surgery team for exploratory laparotomy

title: BE29519-MCQ-6
content: A 29-year-old woman arrives at the emergency department after jumping from the second floor of a burning building. Upon presentation, she is obtunded and hemodynamically unstable. Her condition, however, stabilizes after transfusion of two units of packed red blood cells and two units of fresh, frozen plasma. She is found to have a subdural hematoma and a splenic laceration, which compels transfer to the intensive care unit for observation. On the secondary survey, significant ecchymosis, swelling, and evolving fracture blisters are noted of the right ankle. The right foot has dopplerable signals over both the posterior tibial and dorsalis pedis arteries. An AP radiograph of the right ankle is shown in Figures.

title: BE29519-MCQ-9
content: A 37-year-old male presents to the emergency department after a fall from 20 ft. Figures below depict an AP radiograph of the patient’s right knee. The skin about the knee is intact, however, there is significant ecchymosis and evolving hemorrhagic blisters noted medially. ABI measures 1.1 and this appears to be an isolated injury.

title: BE29519-MCQ-19
content: A 54-year-old female comes to your office with a chief complaint of a painful left palm. When further questioned, she mentioned that she has difficulty moving her finger first thing in the morning and occasionally finds that the finger catches, and she has difficulty opening the palm. Review of systems is negative and the patient reports that she is in otherwise good health. This has been going on the past 6 to 8 weeks.

title: BE29519-MCQ-37
content: A 56-year-old man presents to you with a chief complaint of severe right buttock, posterior thigh, and lower leg pain for 12 weeks. It radiates to the lateral aspect of his foot, and it is worse with sitting or standing for prolonged periods and with walking. Now over the past 2 weeks, he reports difficulty with toe push-off on the right side. Treatment so far has been nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAID), physical therapy, and an epidural injection without significant relief. Physical examination findings include 4/5 right ankle plantar flexion, a positive straight leg raise on the right, and an absent right Achilles tendon reflex. Images of his lumbar spine are shown in Figures 37A and B.

title: BE29519-MCQ-39
content: You are called to the emergency department to evaluate a 32-year-old man with a history of intravenous drug use who presents with a 2-week history of increasing neck pain and a 2-day history of fevers and progressive weakness in his arms and legs. On examination, he has 3/5 strength globally in his upper and lower extremities and is unable to ambulate without assistance

title: BE29519-MCQ-41
content: A 9-year-old boy presents to your clinic with a limping gait which has been there for a few weeks and the problem has been worsening since then. He takes shorter steps with his left leg and spends less of the stance phase on that limb. Examination of bilateral hips reveals significant limitations in both hips in internal and external rotation and abduction. The x-ray is as follows

title: BE29519-MCQ-46
content: A 16-year-old male came to your emergency department with pain and deformity of his left upper thigh after he was hit by a car while skateboarding earlier that afternoon. His general condition stable. The pelvic x-ray shows proximal femur fracture which then further elaborated with CT scan as follow

title: BE29519-MCQ-51
content: A 6-year-old boy with the complaint of unable to fully flex his left elbow after a fall 4 months ago. At that time his left elbow hit the ground, got swollen and tender. He was brought to the traditional healer by his parents

title: BE29519-MCQ-55
content: A 13-year-old girl with spina bifida has been suffering from crooked right foot since 3 years ago, that is when she started her puberty. The deformity has been progressively worst ever since. Her left foot is doing fine

title: BE29519-MCQ-60
content: A 5-year-old boy with a long-standing untreated left clubfoot came to your clinic. He is neurologically intact , normal motoric milestone and active

title: BE29519-MCQ-64
content: A pediatrician consulted you for neonates with swelling and deformity on its right femoral region. The x-ray is as follows

title: BE29519-MCQ-77

She reports having an infection after the initial surgery, which resulted in debridement of the soft tissue and need for the local rotational flap. content: This is an MRI of a gentleman 48 years old, he suffering from back pain and getting worse for the last 5 days. He also has a fever. He has a history of diabetes mellitus for the last 2 years.

title: BE 181120 - Spine 02
content: Female, 56 years old, complaining of bilateral leg pain in the last 6 months ago. The leg pain getting worst in the last 2 weeks. She still able to walk, but after just a few meters she felt pain radiating from her back to her leg. Normal bowel and bladder function.

title: BE 181120 - SPine 03
content: Male, 40 years old, came to the ER after felt from the roof about 6 meters. He was suddenly unable to move both his leg with motoric 0/5 and sensory 0/2 with intact bulbocavernosus reflex and perianal sensation.

title: BE 181120 - Spine 04
content: A 48 years of age female, complaining of severe leg pain in her left lower leg after carrying heavy stuff. No bladder and bowel problem, SLR 30 degree on the left lower leg

title: BE 181120 - Spine 05
content: This is a sagittal CT scan of a 77-year-old woman, who has been experiencing back pain for about 1 month after tried to lift heavy stuff. The pain is aggravated when she walks, change her position. No muscle weakness and sensory disturbances.

title: BE 270521 - 04
content: A 23-year-old man sustains multiple injuries in a high-speed motor vehicle collision. Among his injuries are a right transverse-posterior wall acetabular fracture, a left open tibia fracture with compartment syndrome, and a right calcaneus fracture.

title: BE 270521 - 01
content: A mother came to your clinic complaining about her 7-day old baby with a flailing right upper extremity. She noticed that the baby’s right upper extremity looks less active than the left side since, after the birth, she also said that it is her first child and the baby's birth weight was 4.200 gr with a breech presentation. From the physical examination, you found that the shoulder looked abnormally adducted and the forearm internally rotated.

title: BE 270521 - Hand 01
content: A 35-year-old male came to the emergency department with pain in his right index finger. He stated that he was working with tattoo needles when the needle punctured him in his right index finger 5 days ago. He reports pain and he could not work because of this condition. You were consulted by the emergency department to address this patient’s condition.

title: BE 270521 - Hand 02
content: A 35-year-old male presented to your outpatient clinic with a complaint of wrist pain, which was felt when he was working. He mentioned previous trauma to his left hand. He also stated that he works using his left hand.

title: BE 270521 - Hand 03
content: Below are the radiographic findings of the left elbow after sustaining an injury of the motor vehicle accident.

title: BE 270521 - Hand 04
content: A 45-year-old woman comes to an outpatient clinic, complaining of pain and catching one of her left-hand fingers. She sometimes has to use help to straighten the affected finger. She also complains of clicking when moving her fingers. She denied a history of trauma and diabetes.

title: BE 270521 - Hand 05
content: A 57-year-old woman with pain in the left wrist after falling down. She held out her arms to hold her fall and she experienced pain right after the impact. Below is the x-ray findings

title: BE 270521 - AR 01
content: A 72-year-old female came with bilateral knee pain. The pain aggravated while walking. No history of previous trauma. Joint crepitation was found upon physical examination. All laboratory results were normal. Here are the clinical and radiological pictures

title: BE 270521 - AR 02
content: A 56-year-old man came to the outpatient clinic with deformity of his right foot. The deformity was gradual, painless, and started a year ago. No history of trauma and signs of infection. There was a history of uncontrolled blood sugar. Laboratory examination revealed an increase in ESR and WBC.

title: BE 270521 - AR 03
content: A 30-year-old active male came with a pain on his right knee after being involved in a traffic accident. He refused to move his knee due to the pain. Upon examination, the knee was swollen with no apparent wound. Here is the radiological examination

title: BE 270521 - AR 04
content: A 60-year-old male came in with a pain in his right hip. He had history of prolonged consumption of traditional medicine

title: BE 270521 - AR 05
content: A 63-year-old male came with a painful, swollen, and warm right knee. Two weeks ago, he underwent a knee replacement surgery. He had fever and initial blood count showed increased ESR (70 mm/h) and leucocyte count (23.000)

title: BE 270521 - Onco 01
content: An 11-year-old female came to the outpatient clinic with excruciating pain in her left knee, she had a lump since ± 4 months ago, and went to the bone setter. The lump gets bigger and more painful since ± 1 week. Figures below is the image of clinical picture and other additional examination

title: BE 270521 - Onco 02
content:
A 37 years old female presented to the hospital with a chief complaint of a lump in her left wrist. The lump is progressively bigger in 6 months. She also complained of pain in the last 3 months. She had a dull pain related to activities. Biopsy had been performed.

Laboratory findings :

  • Hemoglobin       12.3 g/Dl (12.0 – 14.0)
  • Leucocytes         8300 / μL 5000 – 10.000
  • CRP                   0.3 mg/L  (0.0 – 5.0)
  •  LDH 135 U/L (< 215)
  • SAP  36 U/L   (< 187)

title: BE 270521 - Onco 03
content: A 50-years old male suddenly suffering severe pain in his left arm

title: BE 270521 - Onco 04
content: A 16-years old boy have moderate pain on his right hip since 6 months

title: BE 270521 - Onco 05
content:
A 47-year-old female presented to the hospital with difficulty in mixturation 3 months before admission. By then she also complained about the defecation problem. No disturbance of walking. No history of trauma.  Core biopsy had been done.

Laboratory findings :

  • Hemoglobin 10.7 g/Dl 12.0 – 14.0
  • Leucocytes           5380 / μL 5000 – 10.000
  • CRP 0.3 mg/L  (0.0 – 5.0)
  • LDH 450 U/L       (< 215)
  • SAP  64 U/L       (< 187)

title: BE 270521 - Ped 01
content: A 14-month girl with normal developmental milestones walks with a trendelenburg gait. The x-ray is as follow

title: BE 270521 - Ped 02
content: This is an 8 year old boy with Short Stature and knocked knees. The deformity seems to be worsening however does not appear to cause any pain. Clinically, the child has severe genu valgum

title: BE 270521 - Ped 03
content: A child came with the following condition as shown by the picture

title: BE 270521 - Ped 04
content:
An 8-year-old female has developed an antalgic gait since the last 2 days. She reluctantly  weight-bear on her right foot. There was a history of a fall down 4 days ago and an upper respiratory tract 1 week ago. Today she begins to develop a fever and she goes to see you in your outpatient clinic.

Laboratory:

Haemoglobin                    10.5 gr/dl

Hematocryte                     31.7 %

Thrombocyte                    424.000/mm3

Leucocyte                         15.000/mm3

title: BE 270521 - Ped 05
content: A 7-year-old boy fell on outstretched hand. His right elbow is swollen, tender and could not be moved due to pain. X ray Shows he sustained Supracondylar fracture Gartland III

title: BE 270521 - Spine 01
content: A girl, 14 y.o., came to your clinic with a complaint of bent back

title: BE 270521 - Spine 02
content:
Female, 60 years old female suffered from severe low back pain 4 days ago. She still can walk but with pain. Pain is not getting better even when she sleeps in the bed. She denied history trauma. She has a history of type II DM but not routinely controlled. Sometimes she felt low grade fever.

Physical finding:

VAS 7-8

Spinal tenderness around Lumbosacral area

Limitation range of motion due to pain

Normal motoric and sensory of lower leg

Laboratory:

Hemoglobin: 11,5

Leukocytes: 16.700

ESR/CRP:  110/30

title: BE 270521 - Spine 03
content: Male, 20 years old, came to the ER after a car accident. Primary survey clear and hemodynamics stable. Neurologically intact but there is spinal tenderness and skin mark in abdominal area.

title: BE 270521 - Spine 04
content: Male, 40 years old, came to your clinic suffering with low back pain radiating to left leg for 1 month previously. Pain aggravated after lifting heavy material in flexion position. He has been doing physical therapy but no significant improvement. MRI result shown below

title: BE 270521 - Spine 05
content: Male, 32 y.o came to ER due to tetraplegic after fall from 3rd floor building

title: BE 270521 - 07
content: The figure above is the anteroposterior radiograph of a 44-year-old firefighter who falls from his road bike and sustains a closed midshaft clavicle fracture.

title: BE 270521 - 11
content: A 30-year-old man sustained a grade 3B open injury of his tibia with a comminuted fracture pattern around his knee area. He underwent a temporary external fixation and debridement for his conditions and was later scheduled for a replacement of his external fixation into an internal plating

title: BE 270521 - 33
content: The figure below is the clinical photograph of an infant with foot deformities

title: BE 270521 - 80
content: A 6-month-old baby is referred to your clinic for evaluation of her feet. Her parents and pediatrician are concerned because her feet do not look “normal.” Clinically, both feet have the appearance of the photo shown in Figure below. The Achilles is palpably tight, there is an empty heel pad, the arch does not reconstitute with hyperextension of the great toe, and the talar head is prominent in the plantar surface of the foot. you order?

title: BE 270521 - 83
content: You are called to the emergency room to evaluate an 11-month-old, non-ambulatory girl with a femur fracture. On examination, she is in the bottom 5% for height and weight. She has a triangular face, white sclerae, normal dentition, and reacts to your words with turning of the head to follow you. There is an obvious deformity of the right femur with tenderness to palpation and deformity of the left tibia without any tenderness to palpation. There is no bruising or skin lesions. On skeletal survey she has irregular intrasutral bones in addition to the normal cranial bones. There are multiple vertebral compression fractures, a right midshaft femur fracture, and deformity of the left tibia with evidence of healing.

title: BE 240522 - 06/07
content: Figures 6A and 6B are the close-up femur radiographs of a 73-year-old man with nonsmall-cell carcinoma of the lung with visceral metastases. He has localized thigh mild pain at rest and with any range of motion of the ipsilateral hip or knee. A bone scan shows multiple areas of increased uptake. Other femur images in the 2 views show no other lesions. The medical oncologist predicts survival of 6 months.

title: BE 240522 - 22/23
content: A 3 months old infant with Left CTEV was being evaluated following 6 weeks of Ponseti serial casting. Talar's head was fully covered by navicular. The heel was full.

title: BE 240522 - 24/25
content: A 14 years old boy has bilateral painful limp and limited hip motion for 3 months. The radiograph of the pelvis shown

title: BE 240522 - 76/77/78/79
content: Figures 76A through 76C are the radiographs of a 45-year-old woman who had a misstep and noted severe onset pain and deformity in the left lower extremity. The pain is isolated to the left ankle without other limbs affected. A CT scan was performed before reduction and is shown in Figures 76D and 76E. Examination demonstrates a closed injury with a clear deformity of the left ankle. The patient is neurovascularly intact.

title: BE 240522 - 94/95/96/97/98/99
content: A 9-year-old boy presented with a limping gait which has been there for a few weeks and the problem has been worsening since then. He takes shorter steps with his left leg and spends less of the stance phase on that limb. Examination of bilateral hips reveals the significantly limited motion of the left hip. There was no history of fever, the boy was fond of playing football. An X-ray was shown in figure 94.

title: BE 240522 - MST 01
content: A 54-year-old female felt pain in the left thigh (VAS 5-6) when she changed position from sitting to standing. She has a history of mastectomy due to breast carcinoma 2 years ago and followed by chemotherapy. X-ray and histopathologic examinations are shown in the figures below.

title: BE 240522 - MST 02
content:
A 14-year-old female came to the hospital with a chief complaint of pain in her left knee 5 months before admission. She also had a loss of appetite and body weight. A core biopsy was done, and no metastases were detected.

Laboratory findings: Hb: 9.4 g/dL (N: 12.0–14.0); WBC: 6.210 / µL (5-10) ; ESR: 50 mm/h (0-15); CRP: 16.3 mg/L (0-5) ; LDH: 383U/L (<215); Serum Alkaline Phosphatase : 392 U/L (<98). MRI shows no involvement of neurovascular bundles and intraarticular infiltration.

title: BE 240522 - MST 03
content: A 15-year-old male came to us with multiple lumps at both knees and crooked forearms since he was 2 years old. He suffered pain in both legs after walking a long distance and had no movement limitations. He had no history of trauma and fever.

title: BE 240522 - MST 04
content:
27 years woman came to an orthopedic clinic, with a chief complaint of lump and deformity on the right wrist. Lump since 8 months ago, and getting  bigger  and  pain,  patient  still  can doing limited  the  daily activity.

Laboratory : Hb 11,8 g/dL; WBC 8790/mcL; ESR 52 mm/hour, Ureum/Cr 22,8/0,55 mg/dL, ALP 89 U/L, LDH 365 U/L. Open Biopsy had been done

title: BE 240522 - MST 05
content: A 74-year-old woman who presented with a pathological fracture through her left humerus demonstrated multiple deposits throughout the skeleton, with characteristic pepper-pot’

title: BE 240522 - SPine 01
content: These are the AP & Lateral X-Ray of a 26 y.o. male who was involved in an MVA. He has no motoric functions in the lower extremity and feels no sensation below the L2 dermatome. His Tonus Sphincter Ani & Bulbocavernosus Reflex is still intact. He also suffers from blunt trauma to the abdomen and several fractured ribs which are to be treated conservatively by the corresponding surgeon

title: BE 240522 - Spine 02
content: These are plain radiograph, sagittal, coronal, and axial MRI of a 22 y.o. male who complained of back pain and has lump developed in his back since 1,5 months.  5 months prior, he has an episode of lower extremity weakness that render him unable to walk. He regains his muscle strength after taking anti-tuberculosis drugs.  On physical examination, there is Gibbus on his back and you find that his motoric and sensory function are all intact, but he has increased APR & KPR (+3/+3).

title: BE 240522 - Spine 03
content: A 24-year-old soccer player-boy complain of left side low back pain for 3 months. His lateral lumbosacral x-ray shown

title: BE 240522 - Spine 04
content: Female, 34 years old complain about back pain referred to right lower extremity since 2 months ago.  VAS score is about 5-6. The pain gets worse if she bends forward and relieve if she stands. She denied any weakness or sensory problems.  Right SLR in 30 degrees. Bowel and bladder function was normal

title: BE 240522 - Spine 05
content: A 13 years old girl came to your clinic brought by her mother because her shoulder look like asymmetrical. She just realized it for the last 1 month. No other musculoskeletal abnormalities were detected.

title: BE 240522 - Hand 01
content: A 40-year-old man with pain, hyperemia, and swelling after accidentally puncturing his right index finger 5 days ago

title: BE 240522 - Hand 02
content: A 40-year-old male came to your clinic with small and ring fingers numbness. The patient also had a positive Tinel sign at the medial elbow region. He had atrophy of interosseous muscles.

title: BE 240522 - Hand 03
content: Male, 30 years old, fell on an outstretched hand and felt pain, swelling, and tenderness over the snuffbox area

title: BE 240522 - Hand 04
content: A 23 years old male trapped his hand in machinery for 4 hours and now feel excruciating pain despite analgetic administration and numbness over all fingers.

title: BE 240522 - Hand 05
content: You have been consulted by the pediatric department for this disorder.

title: BE 240522 - Pediatric 01
content: This is the elbow X-ray AP view of 6 years old boy with elbow pain after injury

title: BE 240522 - Pediatric 02
content: This is the pelvic X-ray AP view of 12 months old boy with a limping gait

title: BE 240522 - Pediatric 03
content: A 5-month-old baby with deformities on both of his feet comes to your clinic.

title: BE 240522 - Pediatric 04
content: 1-year-old boy with duplication of his left thumb.

title: BE 240522 - Pediatric 05
content: A years-old boy had an episode of upper respiratory tract infection 2 weeks ago. These last 2 days he developed swelling and redness on his feet.

title: BE 240522 - AR 01
content: A 64-year-old male complained about pain in his hips for two years. He is a construction laborer who used to drink traditional herbal medicine combined with analgetic after working for ten years. His hip pain was occasionally felt, especially when he was walking, and decreased after he took a rest. He had no history of trauma, fever, alcohol, cough, or TB medication. Physical examination shows leg length discrepancy and tenderness on both hips without mass and swelling. The range of motion was limited. Laboratory examination was performed with the following result: WBC10.700, ESR 5, CRP 0,4, and ICT TB were negative

title: BE 240522 - AR 02
content: A 68-year-old male came with a painful left hip after he fell at home. He had a history of left total hip arthroplasty 3 years ago.

title: BE 240522 - AR 03
content: Mr. M, 33 years old, is a recreational badminton player who came with a chief complaint of a painful left knee for three weeks after he twisted his knee while performing a jumping smash. He could not continue the match, and his knee was swollen and tender. He has experienced episodes of knee locking and clicking. MRI result is shown below

title: BE 240522 - AR 04
content: A 78-year-old female came with left hip pain, especially while walking. The pain was insidious. 5 years ago she underwent a left hip replacement. No sign of infection was noted. Laboratory result shows no abnormality.

title: BE 240522 - AR 05
content: A 23-year cyclist was admitted to the emergency department for pain in his right knee resulting from a cycling accident one hour prior to his admission. He had a fall with the knee in a flexed position. There was no history of chronic illness, nor previous trauma and medication. Physical examination found swelling and tenderness on the right knee. A palpable infrapatellar gap was also noted. The patient could not maintain active knee extension. The patient was sent for MRI after a plain x-ray ruled out a patellar fracture.
